\nLe petit prince multilingual naturalistic fmri corpus.\n\nScientific Data, 9(1):530, 2022.\n\n[20]\n\nJuliette Millet, Charlotte Caucheteux, Yves Boubenec, Alexandre Gramfort, Ewan Dunbar, Christophe Pallier, Jean-Remi King, et al.\n\nToward a realistic model of speech processing in the brain with self-supervised learning.\n\nAdvances in Neural Information Processing Systems, 35:33428–33443, 2022.\n\n[21]\n\nOmer Moussa, Dietrich Klakow, and Mariya Toneva.\n\nImproving semantic understanding in speech language models via brain-tuning.\n\nIn The Thirteenth International Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR), 2025.\n\n[22]\n\nOmer Moussa and Mariya Toneva.\n\nBrain-tuned speech models better reflect speech processing stages in the brain.\n\narXiv preprint arXiv:2506.03832, 2025.\n\n[23]\n\nOmer Moussa and Mariya Toneva.\n\nBrain-tuning improves generalizability and efficiency of brain alignment in speech models.\n\nIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2025.\n\n[24]\n\nSamuel A Nastase, Yun-Fei Liu, Hanna Hillman, Asieh Zadbood, Liat Hasenfratz, Neggin Keshavarzian, Janice Chen, Christopher J Honey, Yaara Yeshurun, Mor Regev, et al.\n\nThe “narratives” fmri dataset for evaluating models of naturalistic language comprehension.\n\nScientific data, 8(1):250, 2021.\n\n[25]\n\nSubba Reddy Oota, Emin Çelik, Fatma Deniz, and Mariya Toneva.\n\nSpeech language models lack important brain-relevant semantics.\n\nAnnual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics (ACL), 2024.\n\n[26]\n\nMartin Schrimpf, Idan Asher Blank, Greta Tuckute, Carina Kauf, Eghbal A Hosseini, Nancy Kanwisher, Joshua B Tenenbaum, and Evelina Fedorenko.\n\nThe neural architecture of language: Integrative modeling converges on predictive processing.\n\nProceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 2021.\n\n[27]\n\nSophie K Scott, C Catrin Blank, Stuart Rosen, and Richard JS Wise.\n\nIdentification of a pathway for intelligible speech in the left temporal lobe.\n\nBrain, 123(12):2400–2406, 2000.\n\n[28]\n\nMarie St-Laurent, Basile Pinsard, Oliver Contier, Elizabeth DuPre, Katja Seeliger, Valentina Borghesani, Julie A Boyle, Lune Bellec, and Martin N Hebart.\n\nCneuromod-things, a densely-sampled fmri dataset for visual neuroscience.\n\nScientific Data, 2026.\n\n[29]\n\nMariya Toneva and Leila Wehbe.\n\nInterpreting and improving natural-language processing (in machines) with natural language-processing (in the brain).\n\nAdvances in Neural Information Processing Systems, 32, 2019.\n\n[30]\n\nAditya R Vaidya, Shailee Jain, and Alexander Huth.\n\nSelf-supervised models of audio effectively explain human cortical responses to speech.\n\nIn International Conference on Machine Learning, pages 21927–21944, 2022.\n\n[31]\n\nNishitha Vattikonda, Aditya R. Vaidya, Richard J. Antonello, and Alexander G. Huth.\n\nBrainWavLM: Fine-tuning speech representations with brain responses to language, 2025.\n\n[32]\n\nLeila Wehbe, Brian Murphy, Partha Talukdar, Alona Fyshe, Aaditya Ramdas, and Tom Mitchell.\n\nSimultaneously uncovering the patterns of brain regions involved in different story reading subprocesses.\n\nPloS One, (11), 2014.\n\nAppendix A Datasets and preprocessing\n\nAll experiments use a common cortical space so that the trained encoder can be evaluated easily across datasets and participants without refitting. This section details the parcellation of ROIs, the additional details of training and evaluation data, and the exploratory mixed-data run that motivated training on Friends alone (App.A.4).\n\nA.1 Brain ROIs Details\n\nAll fMRI is projected to FreeSurfer’s fsaverage6 surface (40,96240{,}962 vertices per hemisphere; mean inter-vertex spacing ∼\\sim2 mm) [11, 10] and restricted to 3030 bilateral HCP-MMP1 ROIs [13], totaling ∼\\sim41,39441{,}394 vertices (∼\\simhalf of the full fsaverage6 cortex). The 3030 ROIs cover the canonical auditory and language network plus sensorimotor, default-mode/theory-of-mind, and visual regions. We expand beyond language regions to test our model ability and efficiency to learn around 50% of the cortical surface while being parameter-efficient. It stress tests the brain transformer’s ability to scale the output size with substantial increase in the trainable parameters as with the full linear ridge models.\n\nThe 3030 ROIs are organized into 1515 functional groups (each with LH and RH instances), with HCP-MMP1 parcels enumerated for the auditory and language groups:\n\n• \n\nAuditory. aud_primary (A1); aud_belt (A4, A5, LBelt, MBelt, PBelt).\n\n• \n\nSuperior temporal and temporal pole. stg_sts (STGa, STSda, STSdp, STSva, STSvp, STV); temporal_pole (TE1a, TE1m, TE1p, TE2a, TE2p, TGd, TGv); posterior_temp (PHT, TPOJ1, TPOJ2, TPOJ3).\n\n• \n\nParietal language. angular_gyrus (PGi, PGs, PGp, PFm); supramarginal (PFop, PFt, PFcm, PSL).\n\n• \n\nFrontal language. ifg (44, 45, 47l); mfg_dlpfc (55b, IFJa, IFSp, SFL, 8Av, 8BL).\n\n• \n\nDefault-mode and theory-of-mind controls. mpfc_tom; precuneus_pcc.\n\n• \n\nSensorimotor and insular controls. motor; insula_fop.\n\n• \n\nVisual controls. visual_early (V1–V4); visual_higher (V6, V6A, V7, V8, LO1, LO2, MT, MST, FST parcels).\n\nA.2 Training data\n\nWe train on the Friends subset of CourtoisNeuroMod [12, 28]: S=6S{=}6 participants watching naturalistic audio-visual TV episodes at TR = 1.491.49 s, totaling ∼\\sim565,000565{,}000 TRs (∼\\sim234234 hours, ∼\\sim3939 hours per participant). RABBiT is audio-only, so only the audio track is used as input; we use the audio of an audio-visual corpus to keep input modality and recording pipeline comparable to our held-out audio-only evaluation cohorts.\n\nThe fMRI is provided in volumetric MNI space at 2 mm resolution and projected onto fsaverage6 surface vertices, with the ∼\\sim41,39441{,}394 vertices belonging to the 3030 ROIs retained per clip. The released CourtoisNeuroMod data are already z-scored per voxel per run, so no further temporal centering is applied — consistent with the SID shared-basis initialization (App.B.2). Within each subject’s clips we hold out a fixed 4 clips of validation set and a fixed 4 clips for test set (held-out evaluations on training participants); the split is identical across subjects so validation losses are directly comparable.\n\nA.3 Evaluation data\n\nThe two held-out cohorts together include 324324 unseen participant–story instances — 275275 across the 77 Narratives stories [24] (the column total of Table1, with each story drawn from an independent participant pool) plus 4949 unique Le Petit Prince participants [19] who heard all 99 audiobook sections. None overlap with the Friends training cohort.\n\nA.3.1 Per-cohort details\n\nNarratives [24]. We use 77 stories from the Narratives corpus (OpenNeuro ds002345), each with an independent participant pool: four longer stories and three shorter, large-cohort stories (Table1).\n\nStory\nTRs\nDuration (min)\nParticipants\nCalibrated audio onset (s)\n\n21styear\n2249\n56.2\n20\n0.0\n\nslumlordreach\n1210\n30.0\n18\n3.0\n\ntunnel\n1037\n25.5\n23\n0.0\n\nsherlock\n725\n18.0\n36\n3.0\n\npieman\n300\n7.5\n82\n0.0\n\nnotthefall\n400\n9.7\n56\n1.5\n\nprettymouth\n475\n11.9\n40\n1.5\n\ntotal / mean\n6396\n\n∼\\sim159\n\n275\n—\n\nTable 1: Narratives held-out stories used in zero-shot evaluation. TRs at the corpus’s native TR = 1.51.5 s. Participant counts are independent across stories; the column total is the participant–story instance count. Calibrated audio onsets are validated as in App.A.3.2.\n\nLe Petit Prince [19]. The English audiobook portion of OpenNeuro ds003643: 4949 native English speakers listening to 99 scanning sections totaling ∼\\sim9393 minutes at TR = 2.02.0 s on a 3T GE Discovery MR750 (a different scanner from CourtoisNeuroMod or Narratives), providing an out-of-distribution test of RABBiT’s transfer beyond the Narratives recording conventions. The released preprocessed runs already strip the leading silence at audio onset, so the audio plays at scanner-time zero and no per-section onset calibration is required (the A1-LH shift sweep peaks at 0 or +1+1 TR for 66 of the 99 sections; the 33 noise-dominated sections are evaluated at the same 0-TR convention). We use an audio onset of 0 for the LPP dataset.\n\nA.3.2 Audio–fMRI alignment and onset validation\n\nThe released stimulus audio for each Narratives story typically begins with a brief leading silence whose duration is neither zero nor the BIDS-listed music-start time. We therefore calibrate the audio-onset value using by estimating it first from metadata and then try multiple values for the shift on a small subset and then measure the A1-belt response activation start. This is used as a correction for the onset time estimated at the beginning; this onset is used consistently across models. Table1 shows the estimated onset values that are used identically by every model (for 44 of the 77 stories the calibrated onset disagrees with the BIDS music-start time).\n\nIt’s important to note that the audio-onset offset is a property of how the stimulus file was exported, not of the model or the brain — the same number for every participant on a given story. Fixing it once per story removes a confounding free parameter from the evaluation, so residual differences across models reflect model quality rather than alignment search.\n\nA.4 Training with mixed data\n\nWe added the Moth Radio Hour subset of [18] (we chose 66 participants, ∼\\sim113,000113{,}000 TRs at TR = 2.02.0 s, ∼\\sim6363 hours) to the Friends mix, yielding a 1212-participant combined cohort with the same SID architecture (the shared bases Φ\\Phi was obtained from both dataset mixtures while the Idiosyncratic part remains per subject.). During training, we forced a 1:21{:}2 Moth-to-Friends batch ratio per training block to account for the size mismatch between the datasets. Across the four narrative story zero-shot evaluation, the combined model achieves a story-mean vertex-wise rr of 0.1080.108 versus 0.1170.117 for Friends-only (an ∼\\sim8%8\\% relative drop). The combined model matches Friends-only on Friends-side validation loss, ruling out undertraining. We have also tried per-subject Full-rank alternatives (see Sec.3.6) and got similar behavior. This suggests that mixing datasets during training is not straightforward and scaling law doesn’t apply linearly regardless of the training data sources, complementary to the findings in [23]; thus, we defer this to future work.\n\nAppendix B Shared–Idiosyncratic diagnostic and SID details\n\nThe SID readout is motivated by a simple empirical observation: some cortical regions are well predicted by the group-mean response across listeners, while others lose reliability sharply when the target listener is excluded from that mean.\n\nB.1 The shared–idiosyncratic diagnostic\n\nFor each ROI ii and subject ss with stimulus-aligned response yi(s)∈ℝT×Viy^{(s)}_{i}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times V_{i}}, we compute the vertex-averaged Pearson correlation between yi(s)y^{(s)}_{i} and the cohort-mean response y¯i\\bar{y}_{i} (including subject ss), then repeat with the leave-one-out cohort-mean y¯i(−s)\\bar{y}^{(-s)}_{i}. The drop between the two measures how much of subject ss’s response is captured only when they are part of the mean: a large drop means the LOO mean predicts subject ss poorly, so the response in ROI ii is more idiosyncratic than shared.\n\nFig.5 plots this contrast across the auditory and language ROIs, averaged over three Narratives stories. Early auditory regions (A1, auditory belt) and superior temporal cortex remain stable under leave-one-out averaging — their responses are largely shared, consistent with high inter-subject correlations in naturalistic listening [24]. Higher-order language and theory-of-mind regions (IFG, MFG/DLPFC, supramarginal, angular gyrus, mPFC) show substantial drops, indicating subject-specific structure that a population mean alone cannot capture. SID’s per-subject deviation pathway gives these idiosyncratic regions a bounded budget of subject-specific structure to draw on; the shared component handles the regions on the shared end.\n\nFigure 5: Shared–idiosyncratic diagnostic across language and auditory ROIs. Vertex-averaged correlation of each subject’s response with the cohort-mean fMRI when the subject is included versus excluded, averaged across three Narratives stories (21styear, tunnel, slumlordreach) and across participants. Auditory and STG/STS regions remain stable; higher-order language regions show substantial drops.\n\nB.2 SID Bases construction and initialization\n\nThe SID bases are warm-started from an empirical decomposition of the training fMRI. For each ROI ii and training subject ss, we run a per-ROI PCA on 20,00020{,}000 subsampled TRs from that subject’s clips, taking the top M=100M=100 principal components as a per-subject basis Φi(s)\\Phi^{(s)}_{i}. The shared basis Φi\\Phi_{i} is the cross-subject average re-orthogonalized via SVD: Φi=SVD​(S−1​∑sΦi(s))\\Phi_{i}=\\mathrm{SVD}\\big(S^{-1}\\sum_{s}\\Phi^{(s)}_{i}\\big). The idiosyncratic (deviation) basis Δi,s\\Delta_{i,s} is the SVD of Φi(s)−Φi\\Phi^{(s)}_{i}-\\Phi_{i} truncated to the top R=15R=15 right singular vectors — the dominant directions in which subject ss departs from the shared basis. During joint training the bases are anchored to their initialization with ℒanchor=λΦ​∑i‖Φi−Φi(0)‖F2+λΔ​∑i,s‖Δi,s−Δi,s(0)‖F2\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{anchor}}=\\lambda_{\\Phi}\\sum_{i}\\|\\Phi_{i}-\\Phi_{i}^{(0)}\\|_{F}^{2}+\\lambda_{\\Delta}\\sum_{i,s}\\|\\Delta_{i,s}-\\Delta_{i,s}^{(0)}\\|_{F}^{2} with λΦ=λΔ=10−3\\lambda_{\\Phi}{=}\\lambda_{\\Delta}{=}10^{-3}. This value was chosen empirically based on grid log-scale hypereparamter search over a subset of the training data. We find very strong values to prevent generalization and low values to cause basis drift easily, both of which hurt performance.\n\nMore details on the Idiosyncratic (Deviation) bases Δi,s\\Delta_{i,s}. The per-subject deviation basis is built from each subject’s residual in basis-coefficient space: we form Φi(s)−Φi\\Phi^{(s)}_{i}-\\Phi_{i}, take its SVD, and keep the top R=15R=15 right singular vectors as Δi,s∈ℝR×Vi\\Delta_{i,s}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{R\\times V_{i}}. By construction, Δi,s\\Delta_{i,s} spans the dominant directions in which subject ss’s within-ROI response geometry departs from the cohort-shared basis.\n\nB.3 Choice of shared and deviation ranks\n\nThe shared rank MM is chosen as a coverage threshold: at M=100M=100 the cumulative explained variance of the per-subject PCA reaches 0.9930.993 averaged across 66 subjects ×30\\times 30 ROIs (Table2); only bilateral motor cortex (V≈5,000V\\approx 5{,}000) is below 95%95\\%. Auditory cortex saturates by M=20M{=}20, language ROIs by M=50M{=}50. M=100M{=}100 is conservative; M=50M{=}50 would lose only ∼\\sim2%2\\% mean coverage.\n\nMM\nmean cum. var.\nstd\nmin ROI\nmedian ROI\nmax ROI\n\n5\n0.737\n0.114\n0.463\n0.755\n0.978\n\n10\n0.836\n0.095\n0.587\n0.863\n0.997\n\n20\n0.914\n0.071\n0.697\n0.938\n1.000\n\n30\n0.947\n0.055\n0.763\n0.970\n1.000\n\n50\n0.975\n0.036\n0.843\n0.990\n1.000\n\n75\n0.988\n0.022\n0.900\n0.997\n1.000\n\n100\n0.993\n0.015\n0.933\n0.999\n1.000\n\nTable 2: Cumulative explained variance of the per-subject shared bases as a function of MM. n=180n{=}180 cells per row (66 subjects ×30\\times 30 ROIs). The default M=100M{=}100 retains 99.3%99.3\\% of within-ROI variance on average.\n\nThe deviation rank R=15R=15 is a regularization budget, not a coverage threshold: at R=15R{=}15 the deviation basis retains only 29%29\\% of the per-subject residual variation. To reach 8080–90%90\\% residual energy would require R≈50R\\approx 50–7575, granting the readout disproportionate per-subject flexibility. A joint M=200M{=}200, R=30R{=}30 ablation at the same backbone and transformer mostly probes the RR axis (M>100M{>}100 adds at most 0.7%0.7\\% coverage, while R:15→30R{:}15{\\to}30 nearly doubles deviation flexibility; in our experiments, this scaling does not improve held-out performance.\n\nAppendix C RABBiT Architecture and Training Details \n\nThis section gives the full architecture, loss, and optimization details that reproduce the headline configuration.\n\nC.1 Speech backbone and brain-tuning\n\nThe speech backbone supplies RABBiT with a temporal stream of frame-level audio tokens that the brain transformer routes into ROI latents. We use Wav2Vec2.0-base [3] as the backbone in all reported runs — a 9090M-parameter self-supervised model trained on 960960 hours of LibriSpeech — because it is the standard acoustic SSL backbone in the brain-tuning lineage [21, 23, 31] and produces a feature sequence at 5050 Hz (2020 ms per frame), giving the brain transformer a fine-grained acoustic stream to pool over.\n\nLoRA adapters. We brain-tune the backbone with parameter-efficient LoRA [15] of rank r=8r=8 (after ablation; Fig.6), inserted only in the linear projections of the audio-encoder transformer blocks. The pretrained weights of every module are kept frozen; only the LoRA matrices are updated in the backbone over the course of training. This keeps the backbone shared across all training subjects this adds approximately 0.60.6M trainable backbone parameters compared to the 9090M frozen body.\n\nLearning rate and Freeze warmup. We use a learning rate of 1​e−41e-4 with a linear warmup period of 10%10\\% and then a linear decay over epochs. For the first 33 epochs the backbone is held entirely frozen and only the brain transformer and SID readout are updated; LoRA training begins thereafter, governed by the same early-stopping criterion (patience 55).\n\nTraining hardware We use AdamW optimizer to update the trainable paramters of the model; we train with a batch size of 256 for 30 epochs with early stopping available with a 5 epoch patience. The training takes around 10 hours for 30 epochs on a single H200 GPU, with early stopping usually stopping the training at 10-13 epochs.\n\nFigure 6: LoRA rank ablation on Le Petit Prince zero-shot. Group-level rgroupr_{\\mathrm{group}} on language ROIs as a function of LoRA rank. Performance peaks at rank 88 (our default) and is robust across nearby ranks; very small ranks under-parameterize the backbone adaptation and very large ranks begin to overfit the limited fMRI training signal.\n\nC.2 Temporal brain transformer architecture\n\nThe temporal brain transformer is a stack of transformer cross-attention blocks (Fig.1(b) in main text). We chose L=2L=2 layers for it and a hidden dimension do=256d_{o}=256, H=8H=8 heads, and FFN dimension 4​do=10244d_{o}=1024 with GELU non-linearity. Backbone features at 5050 Hz are projected to dod_{o} via a learned linear layer with sinusoidal positional encoding added to keys at each cross-attention. The 3030 ROI queries (qi∈ℝdoq_{i}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d_{o}}, one per bilateral ROI; ∼\\sim7.77.7K params) are initialized to zero and combined with a learned per-ROI positional embedding. Each block applies self-attention over the queries, then cross-attention from queries to backbone tokens (values gathered without positional info), then FFN. The second-layer self-attention is the load-bearing one for cross-ROI coordination: its inputs carry stimulus-specific information from the first cross-attention, which lets each query condition its second-pass extraction on the global brain state.\n\nTwo ablations on Le Petit Prince zero-shot support these choices: depth L=2L=2 is the empirical peak (Fig.7), with deeper variants (L∈{4,8,10}L\\in\\{4,8,10\\}) regressing on the all-vertex aggregate by 0.0080.008–0.0100.010 rr; hidden dimension do=256d_{o}=256 is also the peak (Fig.8), with both narrower (do∈{64,128}d_{o}\\in\\{64,128\\}) and wider (do=512d_{o}=512) configurations regressing on all three scopes.\n\nFigure 7: Brain-transformer depth ablation on Le Petit Prince zero-shot. Group-level rgroupr_{\\mathrm{group}} on language ROIs as a function of decoder depth LL. Performance peaks at L=2L=2 (our default); deeper variants do not improve held-out language-ROI prediction.\n\nFigure 8: Brain-transformer hidden dim ablation on Le Petit Prince zero-shot. Group-level rgroupr_{\\mathrm{group}} on language ROIs as a function of decoder hidden dimension HH. Performance peaks at 256256 (our default); deeper variants do not improve held-out language-ROI prediction.\n\nC.3 SID prediction and zero-shot inference\n\nAfter the brain transformer produces a per-ROI latent zi∈ℝdoz_{i}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d_{o}}, the SID readout maps ziz_{i} to vertex-level fMRI in two parallel pathways: shared coefficients πi​(zi)∈ℝM\\pi_{i}(z_{i})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M} combine with the shared basis Φi\\Phi_{i}, and deviation coefficients ρi​(zi)∈ℝR\\rho_{i}(z_{i})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{R} combine with the per-subject deviation basis Δi,s\\Delta_{i,s} (both πi,ρi\\pi_{i},\\rho_{i} are linear). For ROI ii and subject ss,\n\ny^i(s)=πi​(zi)​Φi+ρi​(zi)​Δi,s.\\hat{y}^{(s)}_{i}\\;=\\;\\pi_{i}(z_{i})\\,\\Phi_{i}\\;+\\;\\rho_{i}(z_{i})\\,\\Delta_{i,s}.\n\nFor a held-out subject the idiosyncratic (deviation) basis Δi,s\\Delta_{i,s} is unknown; we replace it with the cohort average Δ¯i=1S​∑sΔi,s\\bar{\\Delta}_{i}=\\frac{1}{S}\\sum_{s}\\Delta_{i,s}, giving y^i=πi​(zi)​Φi+ρi​(zi)​Δ¯i\\hat{y}_{i}=\\pi_{i}(z_{i})\\,\\Phi_{i}+\\rho_{i}(z_{i})\\,\\bar{\\Delta}_{i}. This single substitution is the only change between training-time and zero-shot inference. Replacing the cohort-averaged deviation pathway with zero (predicting only the shared component) recovers approximately half the signal of the averaged-deviation prediction across the auditory and language ROIs of the held-out cohorts: even when no individual training-subject’s deviation basis matches the new participant, the cohort average captures population-level structure the new participant inherits as a population draw.\n\nC.4 Loss and training details\n\nTraining optimizes the full encoder end-to-end against measured fMRI responses across the six Friends training participants (App.A.2), using the loss\n\nℒ=∑i(si​ℒiL2+λcorr​ℒicorr)+ℒanchor\\mathcal{L}\\;=\\;\\sum_{i}\\big(\\,s_{i}\\,\\mathcal{L}^{\\mathrm{L2}}_{i}\\;+\\;\\lambda_{\\mathrm{corr}}\\,\\mathcal{L}^{\\mathrm{corr}}_{i}\\,\\big)\\;+\\;\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{anchor}}\n\nwhere ℒiL2\\mathcal{L}^{\\mathrm{L2}}_{i} is the per-ROI vertex-wise squared error between predicted and measured z-scored fMRI, ℒicorr\\mathcal{L}^{\\mathrm{corr}}_{i} is the per-ROI correlation loss (11 minus the per-ROI vertex-mean Pearson correlation), and sis_{i} is a per-ROI learned scalar that lets each ROI calibrate its own squared-error weight independently. The anchor term (ℒanchor\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{anchor}}) is defined in App.B.2.\n\nWhy the per-ROI scaled-correlation form. The squared-error term alone produces predictions well-calibrated in magnitude but only weakly correlated with the target on the higher-order ROIs whose response geometry is harder to recover; the correlation term alone produces predictions that are correlated but unscaled, and trains poorly because correlation gradients are scale-invariant. The scaled-correlation form combines the two, so each ROI gets gradient pressure on both correlation and magnitude, with a per-ROI learned scale that absorbs cross-ROI variation in noise floor (auditory ROIs have a much higher signal-to-noise ratio than e.g. mPFC and need less L2 weight to be well-fit). We use λcorr=1\\lambda_{\\mathrm{corr}}=1 throughout. Our choice for this value was also done empirically, similar to the anchor search (see App.B.2)\n\nOptimization. Parameters are optimized with AdamW. The brain transformer, coefficient maps, and LoRA adapters share a base learning rate; the SID bases use a smaller learning rate that keeps them close to their PCA/SVD initialization while still allowing fine-grained refinement under gradients from the brain-tuned backbone.\n\nAppendix D Zero-shot evaluation and Baselines\n\nZero-shot evaluation tests whether the trained encoder predicts the reliable group response of unseen listeners without using any fMRI from those listeners.\n\nD.1 Accuracy metrics and the inter-subject consistency\n\nWe report two metrics per (model, ROI, story). The group-level correlation rgroup(i)=vertex​_​meanv∈i​[corrt​(y^​[t,v],y¯(cohort)​[t,v])]r_{\\mathrm{group}}^{(i)}=\\mathrm{vertex\\_mean}_{v\\in i}\\big[\\mathrm{corr}_{t}(\\hat{y}[t,v],\\bar{y}^{(\\text{cohort})}[t,v])\\big] targets the cohort-mean fMRI; the per-subject consistency r(i,s)r^{(i,s)} targets each individual subject’s fMRI and is averaged across the NN subjects in the cohort. Both inputs are z-scored per vertex over time before correlation. The leave-one-out inter-subject correlation (LOO ISC), computed by holding out each subject in turn and correlating the mean fMRI of the other N−1N{-}1 with the held-out subject, is the cleanest stimulus-only predictor the cohort itself provides and serves as the natural consistency (ceiling) for r(i,s)r^{(i,s)}. It is not a strict ceiling for rgroupr_{\\mathrm{group}}: a model whose prediction is identical for every subject can exceed LOO ISC in rgroupr_{\\mathrm{group}} when the cohort is small or the ROI is highly stereotyped, because the cohort-mean target is itself noisy at small NN but the model’s prediction is noiseless across subjects (RABBiT’s A1 reaches rgroup≈0.55r_{\\mathrm{group}}\\approx 0.55 vs LOO ISC ≈0.27\\approx 0.27 on the headline Narratives stories).\n\nAn important note is that for RABBiT, we use the same audio onset as the other models and add the hemodynamic delay of 33TRs as well, a standard practice since audio at time tt correspond a later fMRI, typically 4-6 seconds after onset [2]; TRIBEv2 does the same but it bakes the delay into its prediction and training from the start.\n\nD.2 Linear and Per-Subject Full-Rank baselines\n\nLinear baseline. The Linear baseline removes everything that distinguishes RABBiT from a frozen-feature linear probe: a frozen Wav2Vec2.0-base, mean-pooling over time within each TR-aligned window to a single 768768-dim vector, and a per-ROI linear layer mapping that vector to all ViV_{i} vertices in ROI ii. There is no temporal brain transformer and no SID; the only trainable parameters are the per-ROI linear readouts. Any gap between RABBiT and the Linear baseline must come from brain-tuning, the temporal brain transformer, or SID, not from the backbone or the vertex parcellation.\n\nPer-Subject Full-Rank baseline. The Per-Subject Full-Rank baseline preserves the brain-tuned backbone and the temporal brain transformer but replaces the SID readout with one independent full-rank linear layer per ROI per training subject (no shared–deviation factorization). This adds ∼\\sim5×5\\times more total parameters than RABBiT (per-subject heads grow linearly with the cohort) but otherwise matches RABBiT exactly. If RABBiT matches or beats this variant in zero-shot, the SID compression has no measurable accuracy cost — the bounded shared-plus-deviation parametrization is at least as expressive as independent per-subject heads at this cohort size.\n\nD.3 TRIBEv2 baseline\n\nTRIBEv2 [7] is a tri-modal encoder over video, audio, and text trained on multiple large public fMRI corpora, with frozen LLaMA / Wav2Vec-BERT / V-JEPA backbones, learned MLP projectors per modality, an 88-layer cross-modal transformer, and subject-conditioned linear output heads predicting onto ∼\\sim20,00020{,}000 fsaverage5 vertices at 11 Hz with a 55 s hemodynamic offset baked into its training contract. Vision modality is zeroed at our inference and must be disclosed: our held-out cohorts are pure naturalistic listening, so TRIBEv2’s vision input is replaced with a zero tensor and the visual contribution to the cross-modal combiner reduces to a constant baseline. (TRIBEv2 was trained with 30%30\\% modality dropout, so missing-modality input is in-distribution, but the model still optimizes for the joint case.) RABBiT outperforming TRIBEv2 on visual ROIs is therefore an audio-only-vs-audio-only comparison.\n\nWe run TRIBEv2 on each held-out story with the released model weights, chunking the audio at 62.437562.4375 s per chunk and stitching per-chunk predictions; the stream is aligned to scanner time using the calibrated audio-onset values of App.A.3.2 with the 55 s hemodynamic offset unmodified. Whole-brain rgroupr_{\\mathrm{group}} on a subset of Narratives stories falls within the range reported in the original TRIBEv2 paper (Fig.9), confirming that our inference and alignment pipeline represents the baseline fairly.\n\nFigure 9: Whole-brain rgroupr_{\\mathrm{group}} for TRIBEv2 across several Narratives stories. TRIBEv2 predictions correlated against cohort-mean fMRI on the full cortical surface, with the inter-subject ceiling overlaid per story. Numbers fall within the range reported in the original TRIBEv2 paper.\n\nAppendix E Few-shot Calibration and Baselines\n\nFew-shot evaluation tests whether a short calibration scan can recover listener-specific signal without refitting a full voxel-wise model.\n\nE.1 Calibration setup\n\nWe use the longest single-stimulus Narratives cohort, 21styear (56 minutes per participant, 2020 participants from App.A.3.1), as the headline benchmark; one participant (sub-244244) is excluded for quality reasons, leaving 1919. A second, smaller-stimulus replication on slumlordreach (∼\\sim3030 minutes, 1818 participants) is in App.E.5.\n\nFor each participant we hold out a fixed test segment (the last 400400 TRs of the story, ∼\\sim1010 minutes) and use a contiguous prefix as the calibration window. We sweep five calibration (CC for short) durations: 200200, 400400, 800800, 12001200, 16001600 TRs (∼\\sim55, 1010, 2020, 3030, 4040 minutes at TR = 1.491.49 s); the test segment is identical across calibration sizes so any difference in test-set rr reflects calibration size only. We report per-subject vertex-mean rr on the test segment, averaged across the 1919 participants with ±\\pmstandard-error bands. Cross-validation across the full story would let calibration size co-vary with test position, mixing the calibration-size effect with temporal-coherence effects; the fixed-test protocol avoids this confound.\n\nE.2 RABBiT few-shot adaptation\n\nRABBiT personalization freezes the backbone, the brain transformer, the SID shared bases Φi\\Phi_{i}, the shared coefficient maps πi\\pi_{i}, and the per-subject deviation bases (initialized at the cohort average Δ¯i\\bar{\\Delta}_{i} used at zero-shot inference). The only parameters updated are the per-ROI deviation coefficient maps ρi:ℝdo→ℝR\\rho_{i}:\\mathbb{R}^{d_{o}}\\to\\mathbb{R}^{R}, totaling ∼\\sim115,000115{,}000 parameters across the 3030 ROIs. We minimize a per-ROI vertex-wise correlation loss with an anchor regularizer that penalizes drift of ρi\\rho_{i} from its pretrained value:\n\nℒfs=∑iℒicorr​(ρi)+λρ​∑i‖ρi−ρi(0)‖F2.\\mathcal{L}^{\\mathrm{fs}}\\;=\\;\\sum_{i}\\mathcal{L}^{\\mathrm{corr}}_{i}(\\rho_{i})\\;+\\;\\lambda_{\\rho}\\sum_{i}\\big\\|\\rho_{i}-\\rho_{i}^{(0)}\\big\\|_{F}^{2}.\n\nThe anchor weight λρ\\lambda_{\\rho} is the only material hyperparameter at calibration time. At calibration sizes C≥200C\\geq 200 TRs, λρ=5×10−5\\lambda_{\\rho}=5{\\times}10^{-5} is at or near the held-out optimum across a 44-subject probe sweep (per-subject optimum varies 10−510^{-5} to 10−310^{-3}, but population-mean held-out rr is flat across this range to within ∼\\sim0.0050.005). At smaller calibrations (C≤100C\\leq 100) it is too weak: occasional subjects collapse below their own zero-shot performance, and a stronger λρ=10−3\\lambda_{\\rho}=10^{-3} stabilizes them at the cost of ∼\\sim0.0050.005–0.010.01 relative loss at C≥800C\\geq 800. We use λρ=5×10−5\\lambda_{\\rho}=5{\\times}10^{-5} in all reported headline saturation curves. Optimization is AdamW for several hundred steps at a fixed learning rate, held constant across calibration sizes.\n\nE.3 Ridge baselines\n\nWe compare RABBiT few-shot calibration against two voxel-wise ridge encoders trained on the same per-subject calibration window. Both follow the canonical pipeline of [16] and [2]: extract per-frame audio features from a frozen backbone, build a delayed stimulus matrix using FIR taps spanning the hemodynamic window, z-score per fold, fit ridge regression per vertex via cross-validated alpha selection on a GPU implementation of bootstrap ridge.\n\nThe pretrained-features ridge uses features from a frozen Wav2Vec2.0-base (no brain-tuning) — the canonical subject-specific encoding setup of the field. The brain-tuned-features ridge uses features from a multi-brain-tuned Wav2Vec2.0-base [23] — a backbone that has already absorbed cross-subject signal during multi-subject brain-tuning training but has no learned readout structure. The performance gap between the two ridge variants and RABBiT few-shot directly attributes RABBiT’s gain to the SID readout pathway versus the backbone. A vertex-wise ridge readout on the headline 3030-ROI vertex set (Vtot≈41,394V_{\\mathrm{tot}}\\approx 41{,}394) and a multi-tap FIR delay basis has ∼\\sim222222M trainable parameters with the 768768-dim wav2vec backbone and ∼\\sim297297M with the 10241024-dim WavLM backbone — approximately three orders of magnitude more than the ∼\\sim115,000115{,}000 parameters that RABBiT few-shot updates per participant.\n\nE.4 No-SID RABBiT (direct fine-tune) baseline\n\nThe few-shot variant of the Per-Subject Full-Rank baseline (App.D.2) tests whether the gains in App.E.2 come from the SID structure itself or merely from freezing most of the model and updating a small head. Architecture is identical to RABBiT except the SID readout is replaced by one per-ROI linear layer mapping ziz_{i} directly to all ViV_{i} vertices (no shared–deviation factorization). The full readout is ∼\\sim10.610.6M parameters per participant (∼\\sim92×92\\times more than RABBiT few-shot’s ∼\\sim115,000115{,}000, but ∼\\sim22×22\\times fewer than brain-tuned ridge). At calibration time we adapt this per-ROI linear readout with the same correlation-plus-anchor objective and training schedule.\n\nBecause this baseline lacks RABBiT’s strong shared-bases prior, few-shot adaptation initially loses held-out signal at small calibrations before recovering. At C=200C=200 TRs (∼\\sim55 min), the No-SID readout falls to language-aggregate r=0.118r=0.118 versus its own zero-shot value of r=0.136r=0.136 — a ∼\\sim13%13\\% drop. RABBiT few-shot at the same calibration size starts above its zero-shot (r=0.139r=0.139) and gains a further ∼\\sim+0.01+0.01 from adaptation, never going below zero-shot. The No-SID baseline only recovers parity by C≈800C\\approx 800 TRs (∼\\sim2020 min); this is the structural advantage SID’s bounded subject-adaptation pathway provides at small calibrations.\n\nE.5 Additional few-shot results\n\nTable3 reports paired two-sided tt-tests across the 1919-subject panel between consecutive sorted conditions of the saturation curve. RABBiT few-shot significantly outperforms the No-SID direct fine-tune at every calibration size from 55 to 4040 minutes (p<0.001p<0.001 for 55–3030 min, p≈0.006p\\approx 0.006 at 4040 min). The No-SID direct fine-tune does not significantly outperform the brain-tuned ridge baseline from 1010 minutes onward (numerical Δ​r≈+0.003\\Delta r\\approx+0.003–+0.005+0.005, p>0.10p>0.10).\n\nCalibration\n\nridge →\\to direct\n\ndirect →\\to RABBiT few-shot\n\nridge →\\to RABBiT few-shot\n\n5 min (C=200C{=}200)\n\nΔ+0.009\\Delta\\,{+}0.009, p=0.029p{=}0.029 *\n\nΔ+0.030\\Delta\\,{+}0.030, p<0.001p{<}0.001 ***\n\n***\n\n10 min (C=400C{=}400)\n\nΔ+0.005\\Delta\\,{+}0.005, p=0.108p{=}0.108 n.s.\n\nΔ+0.021\\Delta\\,{+}0.021, p<0.001p{<}0.001 ***\n\n***\n\n20 min (C=800C{=}800)\n\nΔ+0.003\\Delta\\,{+}0.003, p=0.201p{=}0.201 n.s.\n\nΔ+0.014\\Delta\\,{+}0.014, p<0.001p{<}0.001 ***\n\n***\n\n30 min (C=1200C{=}1200)\n\nΔ+0.004\\Delta\\,{+}0.004, p=0.112p{=}0.112 n.s.\n\nΔ+0.009\\Delta\\,{+}0.009, p=0.0001p{=}0.0001 ***\n\n***\n\n40 min (C=1600C{=}1600)\n\nΔ+0.003\\Delta\\,{+}0.003, p=0.172p{=}0.172 n.s.\n\nΔ+0.005\\Delta\\,{+}0.005, p=0.006p{=}0.006 **\n\n**\n\nTable 3: Pairwise paired two-sided tt-tests on the language-aggregate saturation curve. n=19n{=}19 participants on 21styear; Δ​r\\Delta r between consecutive sorted conditions.\n\nThe headline per-ROI figure (main text Fig.4(b)) shows the per-ROI percent change at C=400C{=}400. Fig.12 gives the per-ROI breakdown at the four other calibration sizes (C∈{200,800,1200,1600}C\\in\\{200,800,1200,1600\\}) on 21styear: the qualitative ROI ordering is preserved, the magnitude grows monotonically with calibration size, and the largest improvements remain concentrated in higher-order language and DMN ROIs (IFG, supramarginal, mPFC, angular gyrus, MFG/DLPFC, precuneus/PCC). Fig.10 and Fig.13 give the corresponding saturation curve and per-ROI breakdown on slumlordreach (1818 participants, calibration sizes {100,200,400,600}\\{100,200,400,600\\} TRs); at C=400C{=}400 on the wav2vec backbone, RABBiT few-shot reaches r=0.114r=0.114 on the LH-language aggregate vs r=0.098r=0.098 for No-SID direct and r=0.094r=0.094 for brain-tuned ridge. Two methodological notes: slumlordreach has a different optimal residual hemodynamic shift than 21styear (Δ​t≈2\\Delta t\\approx 2 vs 33 TRs), and we use per-story-calibrated comparisons throughout; the headline anchor λρ=5×10−5\\lambda_{\\rho}=5{\\times}10^{-5} used in all reported saturation curves\n", "numLines": 858, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 858}}}
